Data summary

Carlos S Traynor

05/10/2018

Data charecterisation

Here we summarise the general features of the lung squamos cell (LUSC) and colon adenocarcinoma (COAD) TCGA datasets. The data have been downloaded from TCGA and the CBioPortal following these links: LUSC: http://www.cbioportal.org/study?id=lusc_tcga#clinical COAD: http://www.cbioportal.org/study?id=coadread_tcga#summary

We will use the following libraries:

if(!require("devtools")) install.packages("devtools")
if(!require("tidyprojectAZ")) devtools::install_github("tsahota/tidyprojectAZ")
library(tidyprojectAZ)

Colorectal adenocarcinoma

First we will load the data and make a basic preprocess, to include later the genomic covariates in the model we will filter the clinical dataset for those individuals that also have genomic measurements:

coad_clinical <- "~/test-data/coadread_tcga/data_bcr_clinical_data_patient.txt"
convert_blank_to_na <- function(x) {
    if (!purrr::is_character(x)) {
        return(x)
        print("Error not character")
    } else {
        ifelse(x == "" | x == "[Not Available]" | x == "--" | x == 
            "not reported" | x == "[Not Applicable]" | x == "[Discrepancy]", 
            NA, x)
    }
}
preprocess_clinical <- function(file) {
    clinical_data <- readr::read_tsv(file, skip = 4)
    # convert variable names to lower case
    colnames(clinical_data) <- tolower(colnames(clinical_data))
    # convert all string NA to NA format
    clinical_data <- clinical_data %>% dplyr::mutate_all(dplyr::funs(convert_blank_to_na))
    clinical_data
}

coad_clinical <- preprocess_clinical(coad_clinical)
## Load patient id all
match_remove_is_na <- function(x, y) {
    match(x, y)[!is.na(match(x, y))]
}
patient_id <- readRDS("~/iClusterPlusUtils/coad/coad_complete_patient_id.RDS")
coad_clinical <- coad_clinical[match_remove_is_na(patient_id, coad_clinical$patient_id),

In the tidy description of the dataset obtained with glimpse we see that we have covariates that may potentially be used as treatment effect : - pharmaceutical_tx_adjuvant - radiation_treatment_adjuvan - history_neoadjuvant_trtyn

Then we have variables that may be considered secondary outcome and potentially joint modelled with the overall survival: - treatment_outcome_first_course - new_tumor_event_after_initial_treatment - dfs_status - dfs_months

We can visualise the missing values of these variables with the VIM package:

coad_clinical %>% dplyr::select(tx = pharmaceutical_tx_adjuvant, 
    rad_tx = radiation_treatment_adjuvant, tx_out = treatment_outcome_first_course, 
    recurred = new_tumor_event_after_initial_treatment, h_neo = history_neoadjuvant_trtyn, 
    dfs_status, dfs_t = dfs_months) %>% VIM::aggr(prop = T, labels = colnames(.), 
    numbers = TRUE)

Unfortunately we might have too many missing values of treatment effects and secondary endpoints to include most of these variables in the model. On the other hand we have history_neoadjuvant_trtyn as potential, lets explore this variable with a table:

knitr::kable( table(coad_clinical$history_neoadjuvant_trtyn, useNA = "ifany") )
Var1 Freq
No 301

However, the problem might seem that the variability of history variable is too low.

The dataset also includes interesting genomic variables such as kras or braf status:

knitr::kable( table(coad_clinical$kras_mutation, coad_clinical$braf_gene_analysis_result, useNA = "ifany") )
Abnormal Normal NA
NO 1 13 12
YES 0 13 11
NA 2 1 248

This table shows again that too many are missing values, what is more the NAs are not informative, i.e. we cant assume that NA means that the value is normal but intstead it means that the test was not carried out.

Still we can use a few clinical variables: - age - weight - stage They might be correlated with both dfs and os in an experiment joint model. Lets visualise the missing values for these variables:

coad_clinical %>%
  dplyr::select(os_t = os_months, os_status, age, weight, stage = ajcc_pathologic_tumor_stage, height ) %>%
  VIM::aggr(prop = T, labels = colnames(.), numbers = TRUE)

Still weight and height are missing in an important proportion of subjects, around 0.15, however, we could run two separate analysis with complete cases and imputations and contrast the inferences of each model.

Lets now have a look at the primary and secondary endpoints: -overall survival. -disease free survival.

We make an explanatory table with the survival package of the overall survival:

We found that in the Disease Free subgroup there are no deaths recorded. This is suspicious of informative censoring, deaths might ocurre before dfs is recorded. We could account for this in our analysis by using a simple assumption: os_deceased equivals to right censoring for dfs.

(s4 <- survfit(Surv(os_months, os_status) ~ dfs_status, data = coad_clinical %>% 
    dplyr::mutate(os_months = as.numeric(os_months), os_status = os_status == 
        "DECEASED", dfs_status = ifelse(is.na(dfs_status), "DiseaseFree", 
        dfs_status))))
## Call: survfit(formula = Surv(os_months, os_status) ~ dfs_status, data = coad_clinical %>% 
##     dplyr::mutate(os_months = as.numeric(os_months), os_status = os_status ==

##         dfs_status)))
##

In this dataset we may potentially also use treatment effects, ecog score, or also secondary outcomes:

  • karnofsky_performance_score
  • ecog_score
  • radiation_treatment_adjuvant
  • pharmaceutical_tx_adjuvant
  • tumor_status
  • dfs_status
  • dfs_months

We can visualise the missing values of these variables with the VIM package:

lusc_clinical %>% dplyr::select(tx = pharmaceutical_tx_adjuvant, 
    rad_tx = radiation_treatment_adjuvant, ecog = ecog_score, kpf = karnofsky_performance_score, 
    dfs_status, dfs_t = dfs_months) %>% VIM::aggr(prop = T, labels = colnames(.), 
    numbers = TRUE)

Among all the potential variables we might be able to use ecog, but with difficulty because it has a proportion of 0.5 missing values.

We can also consider the following clinical variables: - age - ajcc_pathologic_tumor_stage - tobacco_smoking_history_indicator
